[2026-03-15T16:11:36Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01Xx6sR1HmZ6vyiPdBUTSMcw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01E1AvjFqchuCwP9Mb8St2Bw","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-02-20-cloche-system-design.md","limit":100},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2735,"cache_read_input_tokens":36753,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2735,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01SVVaZSHnQ1ti7Bvo3ZMa2m","session_id":"6cfc7d64-9635-4a5f-9cf9-37398c58dd96","uuid":"951b47a3-5d1a-4e68-90b7-32a5c2f4c030"}
[2026-03-15T16:11:36Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01E1AvjFqchuCwP9Mb8St2Bw","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Cloche System Design\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→Cloche is a system for grow-coding high quality applications. It provides containerized\n     6→environments for coding agents to operate in isolation, a workflow DSL for linking\n     7→agentic and script-driven tasks, validated code pipelines, and self-evolving tooling.\n     8→\n     9→This document describes the architecture for the MVP (v0.1).\n    10→\n    11→## System Components\n    12→\n    13→Cloche is a Go monorepo producing three binaries:\n    14→\n    15→```\n    16→cmd/\n    17→  cloche/         # CLI client (short-lived)\n    18→  cloched/        # Daemon/orchestrator (long-running)\n    19→  cloche-agent/   # In-container entrypoint (autonomous)\n    20→```\n    21→\n    22→### cloche (CLI)\n    23→\n    24→Short-lived process. Talks to `cloched` over gRPC (Unix socket locally, TCP remotely).\n    25→\n    26→Subcommands:\n    27→- `run <workflow>` — Launch a new workflow run\n    28→- `status [run-id]` — Check run status\n    29→- `logs <run-id>` — Stream logs from a running workflow (bidirectional gRPC stream)\n    30→- `stop <run-id>` — Cancel a running workflow (signals container with SIGTERM)\n    31→\n    32→Accepts prompt files or stdin input for user commands.\n    33→\n    34→### cloched (Daemon)\n    35→\n    36→Long-running process. Responsibilities:\n    37→- Launch and manage Docker containers for workflow runs\n    38→- Listen to status streams from running agents\n    39→- Record captures (step inputs, outputs, results, logs)\n    40→- Expose gRPC API for the CLI\n    41→- Persist state via pluggable storage (SQLite initially)\n    42→\n    43→The daemon does NOT interpret workflow logic. It knows \"container X is running workflow Y\"\n    44→and collects status. The agent is self-directing.\n    45→\n    46→### cloche-agent (In-Container Runtime)\n    47→\n    48→Autonomous process running inside the Docker container. Responsibilities:\n    49→- Parse the workflow DSL (workflow files live in the codebase)\n    50→- Walk the workflow graph, executing steps and following results\n    51→- Invoke coding agents (Claude Code, custom commands) and scripts\n    52→- Stream structured status events back to `cloched`\n    53→- Run to completion (`done` or `abort`) without human intervention\n    54→\n    55→The agent is told which workflow to execute at launch. It handles everything else.\n    56→\n    57→## Communication\n    58→\n    59→### CLI <-> Daemon: gRPC\n    60→\n    61→- Protobuf contracts define the API (the API is the spec)\n    62→- Bidirectional streaming for `logs` (tail container output in real-time)\n    63→- Unix socket for local communication, TCP for remote\n    64→\n    65→### Agent <-> Daemon: Structured JSON over stdout\n    66→\n    67→- The agent writes JSON-lines to stdout with status updates\n    68→- `cloched` attaches to the container's stdout stream via Docker API\n    69→- Messages include: step started, step completed (with result name), logs, errors\n    70→- Kill/cancel: daemon sends SIGTERM to container, agent handles graceful shutdown\n    71→\n    72→## Workflow DSL\n    73→\n    74→### Vocabulary\n    75→\n    76→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    77→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    78→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    79→| step     | A unit of work (type: `agent` or `script`)                         |\n    80→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    81→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n    82→| done     | Built-in terminal step indicating successful completion            |\n    83→| abort    | Built-in terminal step indicating failure (reports error and exits)|\n    84→\n    85→### Syntax\n    86→\n    87→```\n    88→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    89→  step code {\n    90→    prompt = file(\"prompts/implement.md\")\n    91→    container {\n    92→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    93→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"internal-docs.company.com\"]\n    94→    }\n    95→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    96→  }\n    97→\n    98→  step check {\n    99→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n   100→    results = [pass, fail]"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01SVVaZSHnQ1ti7Bvo3ZMa2m","session_id":"6cfc7d64-9635-4a5f-9cf9-37398c58dd96","uuid":"246dba63-1feb-4da9-88db-a57765cb6133"}
